Day 9 — Replication and High Availability
Replication
Replication synchronizes artifacts between Artifactory instances — for geographic distribution, DR, or team isolation.

Types:

Push Replication — Source instance pushes artifacts to a target instance immediately after publishing or on a schedule.

HQ Artifactory → (replicates to) → Europe Artifactory

Pull Replication — Target instance pulls artifacts from a source on a schedule.

Event-Based Replication — Triggered immediately when an artifact is deployed (near real-time).

Use Cases:

Global teams — each region has a local Artifactory, synced from central
Disaster recovery — hot standby
Air-gapped environments — one-way push to isolated network
What Gets Replicated
Artifacts (binaries)
Metadata and properties
Build Info
Permissions (optional)

High Availability (HA)
Artifactory can be deployed as a cluster:

Multiple Artifactory nodes
Shared database (PostgreSQL)
Shared filestore (NFS, S3, GCS, Azure Blob)
Load balancer in front
In HA mode, all nodes are active — requests are distributed. If one node fails, others continue serving traffic. The database and filestore are the single source of truth.

Storage Backends
Artifactory supports multiple storage backends for the binary store:

Local filesystem — single server
NFS — shared across HA nodes
S3 — AWS object storage
Google Cloud Storage
Azure Blob Storage
S3-compatible (MinIO, Ceph)
